Yes, I like the idea

But still, the Chinese novel part made me feeling like I'm reading something like MacBeth, The Lord of the Rings or A Song of Ice and Fire or something alike about medieval European nobles Because the mental activities part is too much I guess.

Most Chinese classical novels would advance the plots with long poems, many of which describe the scenes of landscape, historical scene spots, how the characters meet, fight, or even f**k (just imagine how popular raps are in modern-day pubs or popular cultures). Okay the poem-writing thing is much too difficult and if you ask me to write some classic poems I could barely say  myself, but even without the poems, most plots are still concentrate more on scenes or dialogues than mental activities, which is much different from western novels, because early readers or listeners got the work to read some stories, so they would like to know what the interesting scenes rather than the long dull thoughts of the character, which is in fact something the philosopher would concentrate in while writing. This narrative tradition could still be seen in some of modern-day Wuxia or other Chinese-style novels written by Chinese.

I'm trying to translate that passage into Early Mandarin (17 c. right? That is the era of Early Mandarin). Still the work itself is great, bravo!







